WEBVTT

00:00.492 --> 00:03.273
<i>Reverie, a virtual reality program</i>

00:03.312 --> 00:05.280
<i>where the impossible becomes possible.</i>

00:05.361 --> 00:08.625
<i>Anything you desire you can find here.</i>

00:08.841 --> 00:11.376
<i>But sometimes, people get lost,</i>

00:11.437 --> 00:14.106
<i>caught between fantasy and reality.</i>

00:14.140 --> 00:15.607
<i>That's where she comes in.</i>

00:15.641 --> 00:17.709
<i>Her name is Mara Kint.</i>

00:17.743 --> 00:22.013
<i>Her job, find the lost ones
and bring them home.</i>

00:22.048 --> 00:24.520
<i>And maybe by saving them,</i>

00:24.599 --> 00:27.738
<i>she just might find a way
to save herself.</i>

00:28.254 --> 00:31.575
<i>[sweeping orchestral music]</i>

00:31.622 --> 00:36.325
<font color="#0080ff">Synced & corrected by</font> kinglouisxx
<font color="#0080ff">www.</font>addic7ed<font color="#0080ff">.com</font>

00:37.263 --> 00:38.715
<i>Previously, on "Reverie"...</i>

00:38.778 --> 00:40.866
Charlie, what are you doing here?

00:40.900 --> 00:43.068
What's your personal
connection to this woman?

00:43.102 --> 00:45.038
<i>She worked miracles
for complete strangers.</i>

00:45.077 --> 00:46.575
<i>Unfortunately, she couldn't do it</i>

00:46.632 --> 00:48.206
<i>for the people she loved the most.</i>

00:48.241 --> 00:50.104
- [gunshots]
- Ray! Ray!

00:50.174 --> 00:52.342
<i>You never should have
suggested using 2.0.</i>

00:52.367 --> 00:53.372
What was I supposed to do?

00:53.403 --> 00:54.732
You were supposed to wait
until we figured out

00:54.763 --> 00:56.497
the derealization issues.

00:56.571 --> 00:57.671
[gasps]

00:57.706 --> 01:00.407
[gasping]

01:02.635 --> 01:05.804
<i>[soft piano music]</i>

01:05.838 --> 01:12.911
♪

01:15.548 --> 01:18.050
[keyboard clacking]

01:18.084 --> 01:21.653
♪

01:21.688 --> 01:24.456
<i>- How do I get started?
- You get a BCI.</i>

01:24.490 --> 01:26.625
That's the implant, which we provide.

01:26.659 --> 01:28.894
Do some training in
virtual environments,

01:28.928 --> 01:31.563
design the Reverie you want,
and you're good to go.

01:31.598 --> 01:33.632
And I can be anything I want?

01:33.666 --> 01:35.701
Absolutely. What are you thinking of?

01:35.735 --> 01:37.402
<i>[sighs] I don't know.</i>

01:37.781 --> 01:39.815
<i>I've been in a bad place lately,</i>

01:39.848 --> 01:42.374
<i>on my couch 24/7.</i>

01:42.408 --> 01:44.509
<i>I can't talk to anyone.</i>

01:44.544 --> 01:46.712
<i>I wanna change. I want...</i>

01:46.746 --> 01:49.081
<i>[sighs] I need an adventure.</i>

01:49.115 --> 01:50.249
<i>Apertus.</i>

01:50.283 --> 01:52.517
[beeping, whirring]

01:55.588 --> 01:58.023
[gasps softly]

01:58.057 --> 01:59.825
Awesome.

01:59.859 --> 02:04.997
♪

02:05.031 --> 02:08.199
<i>[enchanting, atmospheric music]</i>

02:08.234 --> 02:15.507
♪

02:17.277 --> 02:20.045
♪ <i>You've got the look</i> ♪

02:20.079 --> 02:22.447
♪ <i>Of love</i> ♪

02:22.482 --> 02:24.716
♪ <i>It's on</i> ♪

02:24.751 --> 02:27.490
♪ <i>Your face</i> ♪

02:28.614 --> 02:29.981
Hi.

02:30.054 --> 02:32.353
Um... I'll have a Scotch.

02:32.392 --> 02:34.226
Certainly.

02:34.260 --> 02:37.306
♪ <i>...time can't erase</i> ♪

02:37.463 --> 02:40.025
♪ <i>Be mine</i> ♪

02:40.166 --> 02:41.366
♪ <i>Tonight</i> ♪

02:41.401 --> 02:43.769
- Agent Kauffmann?
- Hmm?

02:43.803 --> 02:46.938
I'm Keystone, from the agency.

02:46.973 --> 02:49.074
Your assignment.

02:49.108 --> 02:50.876
Target is a scientist

02:50.910 --> 02:53.712
specializing in unconventional weapons.

02:53.746 --> 02:55.414
It says his code name is Vater.

02:55.448 --> 02:57.357
Like... Darth Vader?

02:57.389 --> 02:58.857
He's developed a new bioweapon

02:58.889 --> 03:01.053
that he's offering
to the highest bidder.

03:01.087 --> 03:03.231
Your mission is to find him

03:03.313 --> 03:05.598
and stop him.

03:05.668 --> 03:06.792
Okay.

03:06.826 --> 03:08.593
Um... do you have a picture?

03:08.628 --> 03:12.064
No, but I can point him out
when the time comes.

03:12.098 --> 03:13.165
What?

03:13.199 --> 03:14.800
Those men work for Vater.

03:14.834 --> 03:17.402
- Hope you're good in a fight.
- What?

03:17.437 --> 03:19.504
[gunshots]

03:19.539 --> 03:21.139
[people screaming]

03:21.174 --> 03:22.474
[audio modulates]

03:22.508 --> 03:24.409
- [gasps]
- [people yelling]

03:24.444 --> 03:27.646
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

03:29.753 --> 03:31.320
Get behind me!

03:31.413 --> 03:32.584
Both hands on the gun,

03:32.618 --> 03:35.187
arms straight,
thumbs pointed at the target.

03:35.221 --> 03:42.461
♪

03:45.418 --> 03:47.085
Did you see that?

03:47.158 --> 03:49.768
That was amazing. So real!

03:49.802 --> 03:51.536
This is insanely cool!

03:51.571 --> 03:54.039
Target's nearby, probably outside.

03:54.073 --> 03:55.140
On it.

03:55.174 --> 03:58.543
♪

03:58.578 --> 04:00.867
Over there. That's him.

04:00.940 --> 04:02.174
Start the car!

04:02.248 --> 04:04.483
Move!

04:04.517 --> 04:06.218
You?

04:06.252 --> 04:08.402
No. How?

04:08.888 --> 04:10.689
- [groans]
- Wait...

04:10.723 --> 04:13.191
[tires screech]

04:13.226 --> 04:15.327
Wait! Come back!

04:15.361 --> 04:17.462
Please! Please!

04:17.497 --> 04:24.770
♪

04:26.539 --> 04:28.407
Get out of the car! Now!

04:28.441 --> 04:34.312
♪

04:34.347 --> 04:35.847
[tires screech]

04:42.121 --> 04:45.090
<i>[light music]</i>

04:45.124 --> 04:47.526
♪

04:47.560 --> 04:49.194
<i>[Brynn giggling]</i>

04:49.228 --> 04:50.215
[gasps]

04:50.248 --> 04:51.581
<i>Brynn?</i>

04:51.641 --> 04:55.877
<i>[dark ambient music]</i>

04:57.000 --> 05:03.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

05:05.812 --> 05:08.713
<i>[running footsteps, Brynn giggling]</i>

05:08.748 --> 05:10.515
♪

05:10.550 --> 05:12.050
Brynn?

05:12.084 --> 05:14.186
♪

05:14.220 --> 05:17.174
<i>[running footsteps]</i>

05:17.265 --> 05:18.965
Is that you?

05:19.125 --> 05:20.625
♪

05:20.660 --> 05:23.895
[phone ringing]

05:28.634 --> 05:30.235
[phone clicks]

05:32.004 --> 05:34.439
- Charlie, what's up?
<i>- Good morning.</i>

05:34.474 --> 05:36.575
<i>A case just jumped
to the head of the line.</i>

05:36.609 --> 05:37.976
<i>Mind coming in early?</i>

05:38.010 --> 05:39.878
Her name is Rachel Kauffmann.

05:39.912 --> 05:41.546
She came in yesterday.

05:41.581 --> 05:43.582
How'd she get into trouble so fast?

05:43.616 --> 05:45.750
A tech looked in on her last night,

05:45.785 --> 05:48.053
found her sweating
and breathing shallowly.

05:48.087 --> 05:49.888
<i>We moved her to the medical unit,</i>

05:49.922 --> 05:52.290
<i>and found that her heart rate
was skyrocketing.</i>

05:52.325 --> 05:53.592
Whatever Rachel's doing,

05:53.626 --> 05:55.267
it's elevating
her heart rate dramatically,

05:55.292 --> 05:57.796
sending her into
ventricular tachycardia,

05:57.830 --> 05:59.673
which could indicate
an underlying heart defect.

05:59.698 --> 06:01.628
We screen for underlying
medical conditions,

06:01.667 --> 06:03.301
mental health issues.

06:03.336 --> 06:06.004
She signed the waiver.
She should've said something.

06:06.038 --> 06:08.106
But we can't let this woman
go into cardiac arrest.

06:08.140 --> 06:10.408
You need to get her out of there.

06:10.443 --> 06:11.610
Okay.

06:11.644 --> 06:14.279
Um... why did we stop walking?

06:14.313 --> 06:16.715
Oh, this is your office.

06:21.988 --> 06:23.755
[chuckles]

06:23.789 --> 06:25.257
Oh. [chuckles]

06:27.860 --> 06:30.762
Space to work, and a private area,

06:30.796 --> 06:32.664
in case you don't want to
spend hours at your desk

06:32.698 --> 06:33.999
in a sleep state.

06:34.033 --> 06:36.601
Yeah, that's probably a good idea.

06:36.636 --> 06:38.837
So, what can you tell me about,

06:38.871 --> 06:41.840
- uh, Rachel's program?
- Nothing useful.

06:41.874 --> 06:44.709
We have access to the imagery
the clients provide,

06:44.744 --> 06:46.945
but their actual designs
are confidential.

06:46.979 --> 06:48.687
They don't have to share them with us.

06:48.712 --> 06:49.881
Generally, people aren't comfortable

06:49.916 --> 06:51.257
putting together a fantasy

06:51.306 --> 06:53.707
if they think someone is
looking over their shoulder.

06:53.819 --> 06:55.620
I guess I'll figure it out.

06:55.655 --> 06:57.023
Don't waste time.

06:57.116 --> 06:59.609
Get in, get her, get out.

07:00.326 --> 07:03.295
<i>[resonant string music]</i>

07:03.329 --> 07:10.335
♪

07:14.740 --> 07:15.974
<i>Apertus.</i>

07:16.008 --> 07:19.144
[beeping, whirring]

07:19.178 --> 07:22.981
♪

07:23.015 --> 07:24.482
[laughs]

07:24.517 --> 07:28.186
♪

07:28.220 --> 07:29.469
[dice rattling]

07:29.517 --> 07:31.418
All right, final bets.

07:31.523 --> 07:33.257
Hold your bet, hold your bet, please.

07:33.392 --> 07:40.465
♪

07:56.282 --> 07:57.949
[clears throat]

07:57.984 --> 08:01.186
<i>[solemn music]</i>

08:01.220 --> 08:01.953
♪

08:01.988 --> 08:03.588
[whispering inaudible]

08:03.623 --> 08:10.895
♪

08:17.103 --> 08:18.912
I don't know what you're talking about.

08:18.951 --> 08:20.572
- You're after Vater.
- I don't know who that is.

08:20.606 --> 08:23.041
Don't bother lying.
You're not gonna find him.

08:23.075 --> 08:25.777
- [gun clicks]
- Excuse me?

08:25.811 --> 08:27.545
Rachel, hi.

08:27.580 --> 08:29.447
Uh, my name is Mara Kint.

08:29.482 --> 08:30.982
We need to talk.

08:31.017 --> 08:33.083
Who the hell are you?

08:33.953 --> 08:36.388
Oh, uh, I wasn't talking to you.

08:36.422 --> 08:37.922
[sighs]

08:37.957 --> 08:39.924
[gasps, groans]

08:39.958 --> 08:43.928
Well, too bad,
'cause I'm talking to you.

08:47.333 --> 08:49.501
[coughing]

08:49.535 --> 08:51.670
<i>[tense music]</i>

08:51.704 --> 08:53.571
- Thanks.
- Back at ya.

08:53.606 --> 08:55.073
You distracted them.

08:55.107 --> 08:57.575
Okay, Rachel, I'm with Onira-Tech.

08:57.610 --> 08:59.310
Um...

08:59.345 --> 09:00.779
we really need to talk.

09:00.813 --> 09:04.249
♪

09:04.283 --> 09:07.419
No time.

09:07.453 --> 09:09.220
What?

09:12.052 --> 09:13.786
Rachel...

09:13.884 --> 09:15.593
How can you be from Onira-Tech?

09:15.628 --> 09:17.962
I thought only one person
could enter the program.

09:17.997 --> 09:19.464
It's a different program.

09:19.498 --> 09:23.034
Rachel, please slow down.
You're stressing your heart.

09:23.069 --> 09:25.804
Not a chance. I feel fine. I feel great.

09:25.838 --> 09:28.640
Look, you may feel that way,

09:28.674 --> 09:30.542
but you're not.

09:30.576 --> 09:32.120
Why should I believe you?

09:32.220 --> 09:33.921
Why would I lie?

09:34.213 --> 09:36.281
People have lied to me so many times

09:36.315 --> 09:38.883
in so many different and creative ways,

09:38.918 --> 09:41.319
I've stopped wondering why they do it.

09:41.353 --> 09:42.654
What's the point?

09:42.688 --> 09:44.022
It's what they do.

09:44.056 --> 09:47.826
♪

09:47.860 --> 09:50.613
Damn it. You're slowing me down.

09:53.199 --> 09:54.733
Hey!

09:54.767 --> 10:00.004
♪

10:00.090 --> 10:01.120
Rachel!

10:01.224 --> 10:03.359
Rachel! Rachel, slow down!

10:03.384 --> 10:07.154
♪

10:07.184 --> 10:08.646
[door beeps]

10:08.681 --> 10:09.586
♪

10:09.611 --> 10:11.116
No, no.

10:14.519 --> 10:16.859
Are you looking for a clue?

10:17.547 --> 10:19.491
I saw you dig through
those guys' pockets,

10:19.525 --> 10:21.326
and since you knew how to do that,

10:21.360 --> 10:23.828
I figured that this must be
structured like a game.

10:23.863 --> 10:25.851
Wow. You're fast.

10:25.876 --> 10:28.266
When I got in the car, there
was a flyer for the casino.

10:28.300 --> 10:30.068
If the room key was on
the guys downstairs,

10:30.102 --> 10:31.448
somewhere in this room,

10:31.473 --> 10:33.607
something will tell me where to go next.

10:33.706 --> 10:35.354
Okay... Rachel...

10:35.408 --> 10:36.908
Rachel...

10:37.018 --> 10:38.229
Rachel, listen to me.

10:38.284 --> 10:40.078
Your heart is damaged.

10:40.112 --> 10:41.579
Out there in the real world,

10:41.614 --> 10:44.249
it is beating much faster
than it actually should.

10:44.283 --> 10:46.514
The doctors think it's because
of an underlying defect.

10:46.539 --> 10:49.721
You need to leave
and have it checked out.

10:49.755 --> 10:50.852
I don't get it.

10:50.883 --> 10:53.211
No one ever told me there was
a problem with my heart.

10:53.893 --> 10:56.194
Well, maybe the doctor missed it, or...

10:56.228 --> 10:59.531
um, maybe it's new, but it's there.

10:59.565 --> 11:00.865
I don't believe you.

11:00.900 --> 11:03.701
Anyway, what I'm doing is too important.

11:03.736 --> 11:05.970
But it's just a game.

11:06.005 --> 11:09.541
No, it's much more than that.

11:09.575 --> 11:11.810
Why?

11:11.844 --> 11:14.979
<i>[pensive music]</i>

11:15.014 --> 11:16.447
I told you.

11:16.482 --> 11:22.275
♪

11:22.300 --> 11:24.088
Go back to where you came from.

11:24.123 --> 11:26.326
I'm not leaving.

11:26.759 --> 11:30.628
♪

11:33.241 --> 11:35.846
It was a spy Reverie? Those are popular.

11:36.260 --> 11:37.561
They are?

11:37.586 --> 11:39.019
Well, some people use the program

11:39.053 --> 11:41.288
to recreate personal experiences.

11:41.322 --> 11:43.957
Others just wanna be
Jedi Knights or cowboys.

11:43.992 --> 11:45.592
Feed stories you like into the program,

11:45.627 --> 11:47.027
it creates a narrative.

11:47.061 --> 11:49.296
You can blast bad guys
to your heart's content,

11:49.330 --> 11:50.422
like a video game.

11:50.461 --> 11:52.984
Well, except Rachel
doesn't think she's in a game.

11:53.034 --> 11:54.635
She's dead serious.

11:54.669 --> 11:55.963
If she keeps going the way she is,

11:55.979 --> 11:57.446
I'm worried she's gonna die.

11:57.481 --> 12:00.555
- Okay, what are you gonna do?
- I don't know.

12:00.580 --> 12:02.924
I mean, the program is
giving her clues to something,

12:02.978 --> 12:05.158
so until I figure out what that is,

12:05.322 --> 12:08.357
I don't think I can get through to her.

12:10.994 --> 12:13.502
Paul, um...

12:13.797 --> 12:15.557
something...

12:15.832 --> 12:18.098
weird happened.

12:18.268 --> 12:20.636
One of the digital characters

12:20.671 --> 12:22.138
spoke to me.

12:22.172 --> 12:24.140
Last time, they just froze.

12:24.174 --> 12:25.775
What else did it do?

12:25.809 --> 12:27.310
Threatened me,

12:27.344 --> 12:29.712
chased me, tried to strangle me.

12:29.746 --> 12:31.647
That's great!

12:31.682 --> 12:33.449
- Thanks.
- No... [chuckles]

12:33.483 --> 12:35.818
They ignored you, because the program

12:35.852 --> 12:37.486
didn't recognize you then.

12:37.521 --> 12:38.754
Now it does.

12:38.789 --> 12:39.989
The more it knows you,

12:40.023 --> 12:42.124
the easier it'll be for you to work.

12:42.159 --> 12:45.394
How does it get to know me?

12:45.429 --> 12:48.798
Just like people. By watching you.

12:48.832 --> 12:52.234
<i>[soft piano music]</i>

12:52.269 --> 12:54.161
Dylan, there are pictures
of Rachel at a school.

12:54.224 --> 12:55.613
Where does she teach?

12:55.638 --> 12:57.506
<i>Recent posts mention working for</i>

12:57.541 --> 12:59.442
<i>the Sawtelle School District.</i>

12:59.476 --> 13:01.677
You know, she's pretty mild
for Jane Bond.

13:01.712 --> 13:04.513
<i>I thought her name was Rachel.</i>

13:04.548 --> 13:06.881
Right, yeah, but in her Reverie,

13:06.920 --> 13:08.684
she's like a female James Bond, so J...

13:08.757 --> 13:10.691
you know what, never mind,
it's all good.

13:10.757 --> 13:12.191
You probably never even heard of him.

13:12.225 --> 13:13.921
<i>James Bond was a fictional spy</i>

13:13.946 --> 13:15.861
<i>created by a British novelist,
Ian Fleming,</i>

13:15.896 --> 13:17.763
<i>- portrayed on film...</i>
- Right, yes.

13:17.798 --> 13:19.071
That one. [chuckles]

13:19.117 --> 13:22.119
Okay, I forget sometimes
that you're a computer.

13:22.290 --> 13:24.570
<i>- That's okay.</i>
- Okay, so...

13:24.604 --> 13:26.605
Who is the most frequent
poster on her feed?

13:26.640 --> 13:29.241
<i>Let me check. It'll just take a second.</i>

13:29.276 --> 13:30.857
<i>I like spy stories.</i>

13:30.882 --> 13:33.007
<i>Alexis says when we were little,</i>

13:33.070 --> 13:35.471
<i>we used to pretend to be spies together.</i>

13:37.024 --> 13:38.625
When who was little?

13:38.691 --> 13:40.192
<i>Alexis and me.</i>

13:40.226 --> 13:41.760
<i>The most frequent poster</i>

13:41.794 --> 13:43.362
<i>on Rachel Kauffmann's
social media stream</i>

13:43.396 --> 13:45.711
<i>is named Anton DeRay.</i>

13:45.898 --> 13:47.621
Okay, Dylan, some other time,

13:47.646 --> 13:49.911
I'd really like to hear
about those spy games,

13:49.950 --> 13:51.075
but in the meantime,

13:51.122 --> 13:52.747
can you please get me
a number for Anton DeRay

13:52.800 --> 13:54.106
and send it to my phone?

13:54.161 --> 13:55.953
<i>Sure. Anything else?</i>

13:55.988 --> 13:58.289
Uh... no.

13:58.323 --> 14:00.324
No, I'm...

14:00.359 --> 14:03.587
<i>[ominous music]</i>

14:03.657 --> 14:05.863
Ray! Ray! Ray!

14:05.898 --> 14:07.198
[gunshots]

14:07.232 --> 14:09.534
♪

14:09.568 --> 14:11.803
[panting] Excuse me.

14:11.837 --> 14:13.037
♪

14:13.071 --> 14:14.772
Excuse me, sorry.

14:17.009 --> 14:19.226
Excuse me! Wait!

14:19.321 --> 14:20.965
Brynn!

14:21.046 --> 14:23.047
<i>[solemn music]</i>

14:23.081 --> 14:24.562
Oh...

14:24.664 --> 14:26.098
Um...

14:26.194 --> 14:27.628
You're okay.

14:27.686 --> 14:29.887
- I thought your daughter...
- It's all right.

14:29.922 --> 14:32.103
Um...

14:32.825 --> 14:34.853
I'm so sorry.

14:36.829 --> 14:43.968
♪

14:44.002 --> 14:47.004
<i>Anton, what can you
tell me about Rachel?</i>

14:47.039 --> 14:48.673
Smart,

14:48.707 --> 14:49.860
funny,

14:49.899 --> 14:51.843
hates it when people say she's nice.

14:51.868 --> 14:53.813
- Oh.
- I watched her go through

14:53.838 --> 14:56.414
a bunch of guys who did not
treat her very well.

14:56.448 --> 14:58.416
Figured I'd be the one to...

14:58.450 --> 15:00.418
mend her broken wing.

15:00.452 --> 15:02.520
I'm guessing it didn't happen that way.

15:02.554 --> 15:04.322
Well, we finally got together,

15:04.356 --> 15:07.058
then she slept with
one of my housemates.

15:07.092 --> 15:09.185
Well, that sounds
pretty deliberate to me,

15:09.210 --> 15:11.062
like she was pushing you away.

15:11.096 --> 15:12.897
Yeah, she does that,

15:12.931 --> 15:14.623
but you gotta understand,

15:14.648 --> 15:17.101
a lot of people have
let her down in her life.

15:17.135 --> 15:18.693
Her mom died when she was young.

15:18.718 --> 15:20.111
Her dad was never in the picture.

15:20.138 --> 15:22.473
Her aunt raised her.

15:24.042 --> 15:25.676
You know, it's weird.

15:25.711 --> 15:28.713
Her aunt died about four months ago.

15:28.747 --> 15:31.349
Rachel was okay. Wasn't a surprise.

15:31.383 --> 15:33.784
Her... her aunt had been sick
for a while.

15:33.819 --> 15:36.587
But then, she went
to clean out that aunt's house,

15:36.622 --> 15:40.358
and when she came back,
she was in this, uh...

15:40.392 --> 15:41.959
funk.

15:41.994 --> 15:43.427
It's like...

15:43.462 --> 15:45.429
you couldn't even touch her.

15:45.464 --> 15:47.131
♪

15:47.165 --> 15:48.933
She wouldn't let you.

15:48.967 --> 15:51.869
♪

15:51.904 --> 15:55.039
Listen, I... I gotta...
I gotta get to work.

15:55.073 --> 15:56.741
Call me please,
if there's anything else.

15:56.766 --> 15:58.496
I will. Thank you so much, Anton.

15:58.573 --> 16:00.240
All right.

16:04.722 --> 16:06.317
Charlie sent me.

16:06.400 --> 16:09.787
Um... do you mind a talk?

16:13.258 --> 16:15.326
Have you noticed anything unusual

16:15.360 --> 16:17.292
since the BCI was implanted?

16:17.338 --> 16:19.873
Weird stuff, hallucinations?

16:19.932 --> 16:21.232
Why?

16:21.266 --> 16:24.335
Reverie 2.0, the version you have,

16:24.369 --> 16:27.772
digs pretty deep into the consciousness.

16:27.806 --> 16:30.241
There's a chance of side effects.

16:30.275 --> 16:31.642
Like what?

16:31.677 --> 16:34.679
Uh, we call it derealization.

16:34.713 --> 16:37.648
Is that as scary as it sounds?

16:37.683 --> 16:39.984
Mm... no, no, no.
It's a ghosting effect,

16:40.018 --> 16:42.792
like when you, uh,
look at something bright

16:42.817 --> 16:44.956
and still see it
when you close your eyes.

16:44.990 --> 16:47.858
2.0 is programmed to recognize images

16:47.883 --> 16:49.627
you're emotionally connected to.

16:49.661 --> 16:51.537
Sometimes, it'll latch onto one,

16:51.562 --> 16:53.731
even when you're not in the program.

16:54.666 --> 16:58.536
Is what you saw
something you care about?

16:58.570 --> 17:00.204
Someone, yes.

17:00.238 --> 17:02.381
How long did you see them for?

17:03.041 --> 17:05.977
<i>[ominous music]</i>

17:06.011 --> 17:07.377
♪

17:07.412 --> 17:10.647
It was just... for a moment, twice.

17:10.682 --> 17:13.142
Okay, good. It's a temporary effect.

17:13.166 --> 17:14.175
It won't last.

17:14.246 --> 17:16.464
Put away anything
associated with the person,

17:16.519 --> 17:19.457
pictures, whatever,
just until the effect passes.

17:19.491 --> 17:22.660
And if it happens again,
take one of these.

17:22.694 --> 17:25.473
They're mild anti-anxiety meds.

17:25.763 --> 17:29.317
Paul, I just emptied
my medicine cabinet.

17:29.434 --> 17:30.835
Do I really need these?

17:30.869 --> 17:34.538
Just until the effect passes.

17:34.573 --> 17:36.615
Hey.

17:36.942 --> 17:38.843
Charlie, Paul says I'm fine.

17:38.877 --> 17:40.911
You don't have to check up on me.

17:40.946 --> 17:41.946
I'm not.

17:41.980 --> 17:44.622
Rachel Kauffmann's gone into
tachycardia again.

17:44.685 --> 17:46.384
You're gonna have to go back in.

17:46.418 --> 17:49.020
♪

17:49.054 --> 17:50.855
Uh, okay, can... can you

17:50.889 --> 17:53.391
help me change my outfit in her Reverie?

17:53.425 --> 17:55.943
[laughs] I can help you bring,

17:55.968 --> 17:58.217
carry, wear, or be anything you like.

17:58.242 --> 18:00.209
- Sky's the limit.
- Okay, good.

18:00.234 --> 18:01.911
Then I'm gonna need a fancy dress

18:01.988 --> 18:03.622
and a gun.

18:06.568 --> 18:08.988
<i>[mysterious music]</i>

18:09.013 --> 18:11.414
<i>[exhales softly]</i>

18:11.448 --> 18:12.582
<i>Apertus.</i>

18:12.616 --> 18:15.585
[beeping, whirring]

18:15.619 --> 18:17.487
♪

18:17.521 --> 18:19.322
[gasps]

18:20.925 --> 18:22.759
Oh... [chuckles]

18:22.793 --> 18:24.827
Oh, nice, Paul.

18:24.862 --> 18:27.830
<i>[dynamic music]</i>

18:27.865 --> 18:35.138
♪

18:47.259 --> 18:48.994
Shh.

18:50.335 --> 18:52.073
Four guys with guns.

18:52.156 --> 18:59.228
♪

18:59.263 --> 19:00.897
[indistinct chatter]

19:00.931 --> 19:06.135
♪

19:06.170 --> 19:07.971
No, he's still show up though.

19:08.005 --> 19:09.706
- You think so?
- Mm-hmm.

19:09.740 --> 19:10.974
♪

19:11.008 --> 19:14.043
[gunshots]

19:16.847 --> 19:18.548
Nice shooting.

19:18.582 --> 19:20.316
I used to work with the police.

19:20.351 --> 19:23.086
- We got training.
- [gun splashes]

19:23.120 --> 19:25.488
- Why'd you do that?
- I hate guns.

19:25.561 --> 19:28.363
Why would someone who hates
guns work for the police?

19:28.426 --> 19:30.360
Well, I didn't hate them
when I got started,

19:30.394 --> 19:33.511
but then my sister and niece
got killed by one.

19:33.697 --> 19:36.519
Is that supposed to
make me feel sorry for you?

19:36.600 --> 19:38.735
Look, I'm not here to stop you.

19:38.769 --> 19:40.757
I just wanna talk, okay?

19:40.782 --> 19:41.992
Can we do that?

19:42.017 --> 19:43.406
Are you looking for another clue?

19:43.441 --> 19:45.975
No, I know what to do.

19:46.010 --> 19:49.345
The boat's GPS has the last
location of where it went.

19:49.380 --> 19:51.166
If I can figure out how to turn it on,

19:51.191 --> 19:52.882
it'll take me there.

19:52.917 --> 19:54.250
What happens then?

19:54.285 --> 19:56.086
If I'm right,

19:56.120 --> 19:58.054
I find Vater.

19:58.089 --> 20:00.256
Vater? Like Darth Vader?

20:00.291 --> 20:01.925
[scoffs] No.

20:01.959 --> 20:04.160
Well, then who? Who is that?

20:07.031 --> 20:10.100
Rachel, why'd you wanna be a spy?

20:10.134 --> 20:11.601
Spies are tough.

20:11.635 --> 20:14.537
They kick ass, they work alone.

20:14.572 --> 20:17.006
They know that everybody lies to them.

20:17.041 --> 20:19.242
So you wanted a spy story,

20:19.276 --> 20:21.055
and the program made you one,

20:21.080 --> 20:23.814
but then it became something more.

20:24.548 --> 20:27.658
This program is magical.

20:27.918 --> 20:31.121
Things happen here
that you can't explain.

20:31.155 --> 20:33.623
Amazing things can happen here.

20:33.657 --> 20:36.726
What amazing things are you waiting for?

20:36.760 --> 20:38.695
[beeping]

20:41.665 --> 20:44.067
Something happened when you
cleaned your aunt's house.

20:44.101 --> 20:45.969
Oh, my God, who told you that?

20:46.003 --> 20:48.638
Something happened. What was it?

20:48.672 --> 20:50.707
Nothing, except that once again,

20:50.741 --> 20:52.968
I learned the bitter lesson
that you should never, ever

20:53.007 --> 20:54.310
- trust anyone...
- Did your aunt lie to you?

20:54.345 --> 20:55.478
Especially the people
who tell you you should.

20:55.513 --> 20:56.708
Did she hide something from you?

20:56.733 --> 20:59.449
Was it something that
had to do with your mother?

20:59.483 --> 21:01.397
Is your mother connected to Vater?

21:01.422 --> 21:03.820
- Stop it! Just stop it!
- Rachel, listen to me,

21:03.854 --> 21:05.555
you are in danger of
going into cardiac arrest.

21:05.589 --> 21:08.202
You could die. You have to stop.

21:08.227 --> 21:10.160
You told me you wouldn't ask me to stop.

21:10.194 --> 21:12.486
Get off this boat.

21:12.917 --> 21:14.217
Let me stay.

21:14.331 --> 21:16.266
- [gun clicks]
- No.

21:16.300 --> 21:19.836
<i>[tense music]</i>

21:19.870 --> 21:21.468
That's not real.

21:21.539 --> 21:24.281
Then how come I can feel it in my hands?

21:24.406 --> 21:27.054
If I shoot you in my Reverie,
do you die?

21:27.178 --> 21:29.148
Do you wake up?

21:29.313 --> 21:31.080
What do you think happens?

21:31.115 --> 21:36.653
♪

21:42.560 --> 21:44.827
[elevator dings, doors open]

21:47.331 --> 21:48.731
Mara...

21:50.034 --> 21:52.101
This is Monica Shaw,
one of our investors.

21:52.136 --> 21:54.270
Monica, Mara Kint.

21:54.305 --> 21:56.472
- Hello.
- A pleasure, Mara.

21:56.507 --> 21:59.475
I very much looked forward
to meeting you.

21:59.510 --> 22:00.877
Really? Why?

22:00.911 --> 22:03.680
I heard about your
success with Tony Linton.

22:03.714 --> 22:05.048
Excellent work.

22:05.082 --> 22:06.783
- Congratulations.
- Thank you.

22:06.817 --> 22:09.619
Word travels fast.

22:09.653 --> 22:10.887
Oh, don't blame Charlie.

22:10.921 --> 22:13.890
It's my job to keep
an eye on operations.

22:13.924 --> 22:16.960
- Should I be nervous?
- Of course not.

22:18.045 --> 22:19.846
Can I talk to you a second?

22:19.942 --> 22:21.910
Excuse us.

22:21.999 --> 22:23.566
Who is that?

22:23.601 --> 22:26.736
My worry, not yours.

22:26.770 --> 22:29.572
- Any more side effects?
- No.

22:29.607 --> 22:32.242
Anyway, Paul said that
they're temporary.

22:32.276 --> 22:33.509
[panel beeps]

22:33.544 --> 22:35.378
Temporary if you follow instructions,

22:35.412 --> 22:38.414
which in my experience
is not something you do.

22:38.449 --> 22:40.216
I'll be fine.

22:40.251 --> 22:44.053
That device in your brain
is incredibly powerful, Mara.

22:44.088 --> 22:46.923
Don't mess with it.

22:46.957 --> 22:49.692
The doctors tried
a new medication on Rachel.

22:49.727 --> 22:52.996
It calmed her heart down,
for now at least.

22:53.030 --> 22:54.731
Go home.

22:54.765 --> 22:56.399
Get some rest.

22:56.433 --> 22:59.402
<i>[solemn music]</i>

22:59.436 --> 23:05.008
♪

23:05.042 --> 23:08.778
Uh, why are you so concerned
about her, Charlie?

23:08.812 --> 23:11.514
She's running around
in other people's brains,

23:11.548 --> 23:15.251
using a technology we barely understand.

23:15.286 --> 23:16.786
You don't think that's concerning?

23:16.820 --> 23:18.747
You've never mentioned being concerned

23:18.807 --> 23:21.247
about the technology before.

23:22.092 --> 23:25.395
Why are you so worried
about her, Charlie?

23:25.429 --> 23:27.263
Let's go.

23:27.298 --> 23:34.537
♪

23:38.809 --> 23:41.244
<i>[Brynn giggling, footsteps running]</i>

23:41.278 --> 23:44.247
<i>[ominous music]</i>

23:44.281 --> 23:51.554
♪

24:19.216 --> 24:21.117
[kettle whistles]

24:32.503 --> 24:34.667
<i>Rachel's mother was Miriam Kauffmann.</i>

24:34.761 --> 24:37.136
<i>She died in 1993 of cervical cancer.</i>

24:37.175 --> 24:38.608
<i>She was 31 years old.</i>

24:38.643 --> 24:41.478
- Anything else about her?
<i>- Not really.</i>

24:41.512 --> 24:43.329
Okay, how many times is Miriam mentioned

24:43.354 --> 24:45.135
in Rachel's social media posts?

24:45.160 --> 24:46.244
<i>Three times:</i>

24:46.276 --> 24:49.240
<i>eight, five, and four years ago.</i>

24:49.274 --> 24:50.571
Not more recently?

24:50.632 --> 24:53.301
Like, maybe, four months ago,
when her aunt died?

24:53.360 --> 24:54.859
<i>Nope.</i>

24:58.358 --> 25:00.259
Okay, what do you get

25:00.293 --> 25:01.978
when you search Miriam

25:02.041 --> 25:04.096
with the word Vater?

25:04.131 --> 25:05.598
<i>No hits.</i>

25:05.632 --> 25:07.099
But what do you get on Vater alone?

25:07.134 --> 25:09.009
<i>According to one dictionary,</i>

25:09.050 --> 25:10.812
<i>it can mean a Valentine's Day hater,</i>

25:10.837 --> 25:13.105
<i>or the act of drinking a foul liquid.</i>

25:13.140 --> 25:15.274
Okay, well, that's not helpful.

25:15.479 --> 25:17.180
<i>It's a common name in Germany,</i>

25:17.235 --> 25:19.804
<i>but it's pronounced differently there.</i>

25:19.838 --> 25:22.456
- How is it pronounced?
<i>- Vah-ter.</i>

25:22.504 --> 25:25.272
And what does that mean in English?

25:25.306 --> 25:26.773
She mispronounced the name.

25:26.808 --> 25:28.742
She thought it was Vater.

25:28.776 --> 25:31.345
- Like Darth Vader?
- Yeah, exactly.

25:31.379 --> 25:33.180
But it's "Vah-ter,"

25:33.214 --> 25:34.915
German for father.

25:34.949 --> 25:36.863
Well, Kauffmann is a German name.

25:36.917 --> 25:38.819
I can see the program making that leap.

25:38.853 --> 25:42.022
I think that she thinks that the program

25:42.056 --> 25:43.590
is leading her to her father.

25:43.625 --> 25:45.994
Is that possible?

25:46.971 --> 25:49.434
The program's designed
to give you what you want,

25:49.509 --> 25:52.966
either what you say you want
or what it senses you need.

25:53.001 --> 25:56.170
So if the program sensed
that need in her,

25:56.204 --> 25:59.039
sure, it might introduce
her father to the narrative.

25:59.073 --> 26:02.476
But it would need data
about him to work from.

26:02.510 --> 26:04.068
But there's no sign of him anywhere.

26:04.093 --> 26:07.398
On her birth certificate,
he's listed as John Doe.

26:08.061 --> 26:09.851
If you're right,

26:09.929 --> 26:11.485
and the program put him in the Reverie,

26:11.519 --> 26:13.353
then it must have found something.

26:13.388 --> 26:15.222
<i>[pensive music]</i>

26:15.321 --> 26:17.089
You know, it might be on her laptop.

26:17.114 --> 26:18.748
The design app would be there,

26:18.782 --> 26:20.617
and it pulls data from the hard drive.

26:20.651 --> 26:22.051
♪

26:22.086 --> 26:24.587
You want me to hack into a laptop?

26:24.622 --> 26:26.189
A lot of people here can do that.

26:26.223 --> 26:27.890
But Paul says you're
the best in the office.

26:27.925 --> 26:30.488
He's right, but I have work to do.

26:30.545 --> 26:33.413
Time is kind of an issue,
this has to be done fast,

26:33.464 --> 26:35.798
and you are the best.

26:35.833 --> 26:38.868
- Flattery won't help you.
- Okay, what will?

26:42.172 --> 26:44.641
Do you know that I received
a MacArthur Grant?

26:44.675 --> 26:45.875
I don't know what that is,

26:45.909 --> 26:47.310
but that sounds very impressive.

26:47.344 --> 26:49.979
It's given to geniuses in their field.

26:50.014 --> 26:51.414
I got it when I was 17.

26:51.448 --> 26:53.616
That's the work
you're asking me to interrupt.

26:53.651 --> 26:55.453
Like I said, impressive.

27:01.692 --> 27:03.367
Yes.

27:03.527 --> 27:05.995
Do your parents ever come to the office?

27:06.030 --> 27:07.664
Why?

27:07.698 --> 27:09.999
I would like to meet them.

27:10.034 --> 27:11.801
I was talking to Dylan.

27:11.835 --> 27:14.304
He mentioned things
you and he did when...

27:14.338 --> 27:16.005
you were little.

27:16.032 --> 27:18.800
Is he based on somebody in your family?

27:18.854 --> 27:22.011
Was there, like,
an inspiration there, or...

27:22.046 --> 27:23.780
Dylan is an artificial intelligence.

27:23.814 --> 27:25.782
The question is irrelevant.

27:25.816 --> 27:27.595
This is open.

27:27.818 --> 27:29.736
I have real work to do.

27:37.561 --> 27:40.530
<i>[pensive music]</i>

27:40.564 --> 27:42.765
♪

27:45.202 --> 27:46.836
Rachel found the picture
in her aunt's house

27:46.870 --> 27:48.037
when she was cleaning it out.

27:48.072 --> 27:49.372
She wrote a whole journal about it.

27:49.406 --> 27:50.873
It's all right there on the laptop.

27:50.908 --> 27:52.842
That's her mother, and she thinks

27:52.876 --> 27:55.345
that that man right there is her father.

27:55.379 --> 27:56.546
Mm-hm.

27:56.580 --> 27:59.443
Well, based on appearances,
I'd say she could be right.

27:59.468 --> 28:01.404
The aunt never showed her the picture,

28:01.429 --> 28:03.115
denied knowing anything
about the father,

28:03.140 --> 28:05.693
so then, when she found it,
she went into a rage.

28:05.718 --> 28:07.957
Can't blame her there.

28:07.991 --> 28:09.125
Did she look for him?

28:09.159 --> 28:11.060
Uh, she hired detectives,

28:11.095 --> 28:13.945
did DNA registry,
even talked to a psychic.

28:13.970 --> 28:15.865
She didn't find anything.

28:15.899 --> 28:17.400
So she's desperate.

28:17.434 --> 28:20.287
Isolated. Disconnected.

28:20.357 --> 28:22.129
This is the only person
that she has left,

28:22.154 --> 28:23.340
and she couldn't find him,

28:23.365 --> 28:25.007
until he turned up in her Reverie.

28:25.042 --> 28:26.876
That's what the program
was picking up on, Charlie.

28:26.910 --> 28:28.511
That's why he's there.

28:28.545 --> 28:30.573
She needs him.

28:31.081 --> 28:33.049
I know you're telling me this
for a reason.

28:33.083 --> 28:36.089
- I want you to find him.
- [laughs]

28:36.754 --> 28:39.589
I am not police anymore, Mara.

28:39.623 --> 28:41.224
And she already did a search.

28:41.258 --> 28:43.926
With rent-by-the-hour
private detectives.

28:43.961 --> 28:45.424
They're useless, Charlie.

28:45.449 --> 28:47.824
Nobody's looked for him, not seriously.

28:48.532 --> 28:51.401
You brought me here
to help people, right?

28:51.435 --> 28:52.769
Yeah.

28:52.803 --> 28:54.237
She needs help.

28:54.271 --> 28:56.339
[sighs]

28:58.041 --> 28:59.575
What are you gonna do?

28:59.610 --> 29:01.411
I'm gonna go back in.

29:01.436 --> 29:05.773
[whirring, whooshes]

29:05.816 --> 29:08.084
[waves crashing]

29:32.943 --> 29:34.911
I'm not here to get in your way.

29:34.945 --> 29:37.647
Then what are you here to do?

29:37.681 --> 29:39.482
I get it.

29:39.516 --> 29:42.318
You tell people to leave,
you push them away,

29:42.352 --> 29:45.455
but you don't mean it, not really.

29:45.489 --> 29:47.156
<i>[gentle music]</i>

29:47.191 --> 29:49.097
I didn't.

29:50.093 --> 29:51.954
When I was drunk and grieving

29:51.979 --> 29:54.338
and I was staying in my room
and ignoring my calls,

29:54.363 --> 29:56.386
telling my friends to leave,

29:56.467 --> 29:58.503
what I really wanted...

29:59.536 --> 30:01.337
what I really hoped...

30:01.371 --> 30:03.005
♪

30:03.040 --> 30:05.248
Was that one, just one,

30:05.509 --> 30:07.577
would ignore me and stay.

30:07.611 --> 30:09.412
♪

30:10.201 --> 30:12.360
And that's what I'm gonna do for you,

30:13.375 --> 30:15.227
whether you like it or not.

30:15.385 --> 30:21.991
♪

30:33.380 --> 30:35.848
- Dylan?
<i>- Yes, Charlie?</i>

30:36.538 --> 30:38.339
Can you run a facial recognition program

30:38.374 --> 30:41.221
- on this man here?
<i>- Sure. How old is the picture?</i>

30:41.256 --> 30:42.327
25 years.

30:42.374 --> 30:44.158
<i>I'll have to compensate for the aging.</i>

30:44.192 --> 30:46.994
<i>- It'll take a minute.</i>
- Do your best.

30:47.028 --> 30:48.562
<i>Charlie...</i>

30:48.596 --> 30:50.564
<i>why do you work with me
in the public areas?</i>

30:50.598 --> 30:52.258
<i>If you let me access your office,</i>

30:52.283 --> 30:53.767
<i>we could do this at your desk.</i>

30:53.802 --> 30:56.904
I like you, Dylan, but I'm
not letting you in my office.

30:56.938 --> 30:58.572
<i>Why not?</i>

30:58.613 --> 31:00.877
- Man needs his privacy.
<i>- Okay.</i>

31:00.902 --> 31:04.981
<i>Facial recognition returns
approximately 310,000 hits.</i>

31:05.006 --> 31:07.408
<i>The age difference makes it hard.</i>

31:07.442 --> 31:09.490
Hmm...

31:09.611 --> 31:11.712
You see the hand on the lower right?

31:11.746 --> 31:13.881
<i>[gentle music]</i>

31:13.915 --> 31:16.077
The one that's almost out of frame?

31:16.093 --> 31:17.426
Enlarge that three times.

31:17.461 --> 31:19.362
<i>Okay.</i>

31:19.396 --> 31:21.230
Now the ring on the middle finger,

31:21.265 --> 31:22.598
just that.

31:22.633 --> 31:25.434
♪

31:25.469 --> 31:27.953
That's a school ring.

31:28.272 --> 31:29.772
Can you read the writing on it?

31:29.806 --> 31:33.543
<i>It says "Sun Central High 1986."</i>

31:33.577 --> 31:35.111
[chuckles]

31:35.145 --> 31:36.512
♪

31:36.547 --> 31:39.185
You know, I had a case
about 15 years ago,

31:39.650 --> 31:42.084
decomposed body, no head,

31:42.386 --> 31:44.037
but there was a ring,

31:44.221 --> 31:46.414
and that was all we needed.

31:46.557 --> 31:48.291
You know what I'm on, Dylan?

31:48.325 --> 31:49.792
<i>What, Charlie?</i>

31:49.826 --> 31:51.594
The march to victory.

31:51.628 --> 31:55.431
♪

31:55.465 --> 31:58.434
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

31:58.468 --> 32:02.605
♪

32:02.639 --> 32:04.707
[door creaks]

32:04.741 --> 32:12.014
♪

32:23.160 --> 32:24.648
Hey.

32:24.828 --> 32:28.297
You can put the gun down.
Nobody else is here.

32:28.465 --> 32:30.333
Come on down.

32:30.367 --> 32:33.336
<i>[atmospheric music]</i>

32:33.370 --> 32:41.310
♪

32:41.345 --> 32:42.778
You found me.

32:42.813 --> 32:45.014
Congratulations, kiddo.

32:45.048 --> 32:47.583
Make yourself comfortable. Have a seat.

33:02.699 --> 33:05.237
I know you have questions, so...

33:05.469 --> 33:08.464
go ahead, hit me, shoot.

33:11.208 --> 33:12.985
Are you...

33:13.210 --> 33:15.313
are you my father?

33:15.412 --> 33:16.665
I mean, I know...

33:16.747 --> 33:18.548
I'm not crazy. You're not my father.

33:18.610 --> 33:20.290
You're a digital thing.

33:20.360 --> 33:22.924
But in the real world...

33:23.253 --> 33:25.065
are you my father?

33:25.422 --> 33:27.643
What do you think?

33:28.258 --> 33:30.018
Yes.

33:30.160 --> 33:31.924
You look so much...

33:32.029 --> 33:35.231
I mean, that's my nose.

33:35.393 --> 33:37.963
Ever since I saw that picture, I felt...

33:38.068 --> 33:40.221
I feel like I've known that...

33:40.337 --> 33:42.343
you're my dad.

33:42.843 --> 33:45.124
Then I am, kiddo.

33:45.442 --> 33:47.702
You're right.

33:47.911 --> 33:49.845
You've been right all along.

33:49.880 --> 33:52.682
<i>[soft string music]</i>

33:53.738 --> 33:55.273
Are you saying that because it's true,

33:55.332 --> 33:57.605
or because it's what I wanna hear?

33:57.688 --> 33:59.934
Is there a difference?

34:00.290 --> 34:01.924
Yes.

34:02.066 --> 34:05.410
I mean, there are things
that I need to know.

34:05.562 --> 34:07.229
Are you alive?

34:07.379 --> 34:09.764
Where do you live?
Do you think about me?

34:09.800 --> 34:11.266
Do you have a family?

34:11.301 --> 34:14.542
Will you be mad if I try
to get in touch with you?

34:14.638 --> 34:16.405
Do you like reggae music

34:16.440 --> 34:19.875
or corn on the cob or jokes?

34:19.909 --> 34:22.244
Can you tell me any of that?

34:22.279 --> 34:29.351
♪

34:39.629 --> 34:41.751
You see, I...

34:41.931 --> 34:45.810
I have a... have... have
a damaged heart, and...

34:46.248 --> 34:48.248
I'm so angry and sad,

34:48.293 --> 34:49.956
and I push people away.

34:50.005 --> 34:51.786
I'm horrible to them,
I don't trust them,

34:51.824 --> 34:54.281
and I never think that
they're telling me the truth,

34:54.351 --> 34:56.867
and I don't wanna be that way anymore.

34:56.937 --> 34:59.115
I don't. I don't.

34:59.273 --> 35:01.984
I need to feel connected
to something real,

35:02.070 --> 35:04.393
something I can feel and rely on.

35:04.449 --> 35:06.890
Can you help me with that, please?

35:06.923 --> 35:14.196
♪

35:17.367 --> 35:18.968
[whimpers]

35:19.002 --> 35:20.365
[whispers] Rachel...

35:20.431 --> 35:22.399
he can't do that for you.

35:22.472 --> 35:23.806
I know.

35:23.840 --> 35:25.841
I know that now.

35:25.876 --> 35:29.578
♪

35:29.613 --> 35:31.981
You're gonna be okay.

35:32.015 --> 35:34.984
I don't think so.
I don't feel very well.

35:35.018 --> 35:37.071
It's time to go.

35:38.288 --> 35:40.356
I'll be with you on the other side.

35:40.407 --> 35:42.358
Okay.

35:42.392 --> 35:50.166
♪

35:50.200 --> 35:51.500
<i>Exitus.</i>

35:51.535 --> 35:52.835
[soft rumbling]

35:52.869 --> 35:54.837
[monitor beeping]

35:54.871 --> 36:02.111
♪

36:12.332 --> 36:13.833
Welcome back.

36:13.890 --> 36:18.093
♪

36:24.404 --> 36:26.537
- Nice work.
- [chuckles]

36:27.069 --> 36:29.337
How is Rachel doing?

36:29.411 --> 36:32.379
Uh, she's fragile but better, I think.

36:32.414 --> 36:33.881
She saw a cardiologist who says

36:33.915 --> 36:36.016
he can treat her condition
with the medication.

36:36.051 --> 36:37.718
He's sending her home today.

36:37.743 --> 36:40.555
Hey, I got someone I want you to meet.

36:40.580 --> 36:41.618
Hi.

36:41.643 --> 36:43.510
This is Elliott Harrison.

36:43.592 --> 36:45.969
That's his hand in the picture.

36:46.094 --> 36:48.672
Charlie, what have you done?

36:48.763 --> 36:50.664
So you were there, Mr. Harrison?

36:50.699 --> 36:53.067
Yeah, with my friend Alan. That's Alan.

36:53.098 --> 36:54.568
He was invited to see the baby,

36:54.603 --> 36:56.475
but he was nervous, so I went with him.

36:56.515 --> 36:57.948
Nervous because he's the father

36:57.983 --> 36:59.316
and wasn't sticking around?

36:59.351 --> 37:00.618
Well... [chuckles]...

37:00.652 --> 37:02.486
well, you have to understand, uh,

37:02.521 --> 37:03.954
Alan and Miriam had a deal.

37:03.989 --> 37:06.451
Uh, Miriam was single
and wanted a child,

37:06.490 --> 37:08.492
and Alan was a friend
and agreed to be the father.

37:08.521 --> 37:10.795
After that, poof,
they go their separate ways.

37:10.915 --> 37:13.450
Miriam was very clear.
That baby was hers.

37:13.537 --> 37:16.100
She didn't want him hanging around.

37:16.227 --> 37:17.461
They didn't stay in touch.

37:17.566 --> 37:19.537
Uh, Alan never saw her after that.

37:19.571 --> 37:22.339
Um, I feel terrible
now that I know what happened.

37:22.374 --> 37:24.371
Terrible about what?

37:24.426 --> 37:26.310
Um, Mr. Harrison,

37:26.344 --> 37:28.112
this is Rachel Kauffmann.

37:28.146 --> 37:30.347
Elliott knew your mom.

37:30.382 --> 37:32.179
Oh, uh...

37:32.577 --> 37:36.483
they, uh, tell me you're
looking for your father.

37:37.088 --> 37:38.222
I just talked to him.

37:38.256 --> 37:41.483
Uh, that's, uh, his number.

37:41.518 --> 37:43.803
<i>[bright music]</i>

37:43.850 --> 37:45.963
[chuckles] Oh, oh, oh.

37:45.997 --> 37:53.270
♪

37:56.575 --> 37:58.843
Rachel Kauffmann is on her way home.

37:58.877 --> 38:00.344
I heard.

38:00.378 --> 38:03.147
And I... you know, I just
wanted to say thank you

38:03.181 --> 38:04.882
for getting into her laptop.

38:04.916 --> 38:06.717
It really helped.

38:06.751 --> 38:08.986
Good.

38:09.020 --> 38:11.522
And I also wanted to say...

38:12.724 --> 38:14.225
Uh, you're right

38:14.259 --> 38:16.227
to be proud of the program, Alexis.

38:16.261 --> 38:19.530
Rachel told me that she thought
it was miraculous, and...

38:20.699 --> 38:22.831
now I'm starting to see why.

38:23.206 --> 38:26.105
That's why they give me
the genius grants.

38:28.337 --> 38:29.938
<i>Alexis, it's 6:30.</i>

38:29.977 --> 38:32.827
<i>- Ready for backgammon?</i>
- Sure.

38:32.852 --> 38:34.733
<i>[Rationale's "Somewhere to Belong"]</i>

38:34.836 --> 38:36.170
<i>Black or red?</i>

38:36.517 --> 38:38.251
♪

38:38.286 --> 38:40.287
Black.

38:40.321 --> 38:47.594
♪

38:51.650 --> 38:53.733
He was her brother.

38:55.366 --> 38:57.343
They were twins.

38:57.825 --> 38:59.392
Twins?

38:59.607 --> 39:02.006
Must've been about 10 or 11
when he died.

39:02.176 --> 39:04.764
She's never told me
what happened to him.

39:04.970 --> 39:06.959
I don't think she's told anybody.

39:07.181 --> 39:12.185
♪ <i>I should be stronger</i> ♪

39:12.219 --> 39:14.027
♪ <i>Deep down I'm a child</i> ♪

39:14.065 --> 39:16.566
♪ <i>Still trying to find a way</i> ♪

39:16.693 --> 39:19.003
♪ <i>I can hide away</i> ♪

39:19.062 --> 39:21.933
♪ <i>Somewhere to belong</i> ♪

39:22.029 --> 39:25.198
<i>♪ All I really need is somewhere ♪</i>

39:25.232 --> 39:28.635
<i>♪ Somewhere to belong ♪</i>

39:28.678 --> 39:30.446
Hi.

39:30.471 --> 39:32.339
<i>♪ Somewhere to belong ♪</i>

39:32.373 --> 39:34.441
- Thanks.
- Yeah.

39:37.315 --> 39:39.116
Listen, I...

39:39.213 --> 39:42.452
I don't want you to think
that you owe me anything.

39:42.683 --> 39:45.434
I understand the deal
that you had with my mother.

39:46.053 --> 39:48.021
If we could talk every now and then,

39:48.055 --> 39:49.754
that would be great,

39:49.785 --> 39:52.301
but I understand if you don't want to.

39:52.893 --> 39:55.594
Do you mind waiting here a second?

39:55.663 --> 39:57.813
- Yeah, sure.
- Okay.

40:01.836 --> 40:03.870
[sighs]

40:15.950 --> 40:19.272
The last time I saw your mom,
she gave me that,

40:19.748 --> 40:21.037
and I kept it,

40:21.216 --> 40:24.099
well, probably because I liked your mom,

40:24.179 --> 40:26.180
but mostly because...

40:26.293 --> 40:28.506
I hoped this day would come,

40:29.136 --> 40:31.225
and I could show it to you

40:31.639 --> 40:34.319
and tell you that
I never forgot about you.

40:34.568 --> 40:38.004
♪

40:38.039 --> 40:39.461
My, um...

40:39.584 --> 40:41.703
my family is away,

40:41.776 --> 40:44.406
because they wanted to give us
some time alone.

40:44.779 --> 40:46.875
But they're gonna be back
in a little while.

40:47.281 --> 40:48.948
♪

40:48.983 --> 40:50.515
Will you stay?

40:50.618 --> 40:52.492
I'd like you to meet them.

40:52.553 --> 40:54.258
<i>♪ Somewhere to belong ♪</i>

40:54.344 --> 40:55.588
- Yeah.
- Yeah?

40:55.623 --> 40:56.836
<i>♪ Somewhere to belong ♪</i>

40:56.887 --> 40:58.655
Sure.

40:58.696 --> 41:00.197
I could do that.

41:00.294 --> 41:05.265
<i>♪ Somewhere to belong ♪</i>

